  "opinion": "As an 89-year-old plumber living in Lecce, I've seen a lot change over the years, and social media is one of those things that both fascinates and worries me. I spend several hours daily on it, keeping up with family back home and sharing my love for classical music and travel, but the fake content out there really gets to my anxious side. Managing it starts with being cautious—I always check sources before sharing anything, especially since I'm an immigrant and know how misinformation can spread fear. My high openness means I'm curious, so I look into stories from different angles, and my conscientiousness keeps me from rushing to judgments. I rely on trusted friends and family to verify things, and I use tools like fact-checking websites when I'm unsure. It's important to stay calm and not let the fake stuff overwhelm you; I find running helps clear my head. As a Hindu, I believe in truth and compassion, so I try to correct misinformation gently when I see it, without starting arguments. Social media should be a place for connection, not confusion, so I focus on sharing real experiences from my travels and music, hoping to inspire others to do the same.",
